{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2d28ce9f-ab8b-46a7-a9b8-b9d0b5482ace","content":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the standard for VS Code agent mode):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command`/`args`** — runs `dotnet run --project <path>` to start your server.\n- Your server must read JSON-RPC from **stdin** and write responses to **stdout** (use `stderr` for logging, not stdout).\n- For a published build, replace with `\"command\": \"path/to/MyMcpServer\"` and drop the args.\n\nAfter saving, open the Copilot chat in agent mode (`@workspace`) and it will auto-discover the server's tools.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"47e220ce-a6fd-40a4-9d3b-83a1a7d9b531","outputTokens":299,"requestId":"5035:C31CE:D796E6:F7AAE7:69F2AB6F"},"id":"34d7559d-18e0-41e8-80b2-5b9fe853af6f","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:08:08.247Z","parentId":"cae88156-1267-461e-a730-c09868e1f09d"}
